{"title_page": "Isobel Yeung", "text_new": "{{short description|Documentary correspondent}}\n{{Peacock|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Isobel Yeung\n| image         = Nic Dawes - Isobel Yeung - Beverly Chase - HBO Vice.jpg\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1986|11|02}} \n| birth_place   = [[Salisbury, United Kingdom]]\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Nottingham]]\n| nationality   = [[British people|British]] \n| occupation    = [[Journalist]] \n| years_active  = \n}}\n'''Isobel Yeung''' is a long-form [[documentary]] [[correspondent]]. She has covered a variety of global stories, including [[war|conflict]], [[terrorism]], [[gender]], [[mental health]], and [[Re-education through labor|mass detention]]. Her work has earned her two [[Emmy Awards]] and a [[Gracie Award]].\n\n==Biography==\nHer mother is English and father is from [[Hong Kong]].<ref name=\"thew_VICE\">{{Cite web| title = VICE's Isobel Yeung is Breaking The Dress Code| author = | work = The Window| date = | access-date = 7 July 2019| url = https://thewindow.barneys.com/isobel-yeung-breaking-the-dress-code/| quote = Originally from the U.K., Yeung has always had a global perspective, due in part to the fact that her father immigrated to England from Hong Kong in search of a better life}}</ref><ref name=\"poyn_Vice\">{{Cite web| title = Vice goes inside Syria to show what media censorship really looks like - Poynter| author = | work = Poynter| date = 2017-02-23| access-date = 7 July 2019| url = https://www.poynter.org/reporting-editing/2017/vice-goes-inside-syria-to-show-what-media-censorship-really-looks-like/\n| quote = The effort by Yeung \u2014 the child of an English mother and Hong Kong Chinese dad}}</ref> She grew up in [[Salisbury]].\n\nYeung moved to [[China]] after graduating in 2009 from the [[University of Nottingham]].  She freelanced for a number of print publications. Yeung was hired by [[Vice News]] in 2014 and relocated to [[New York City]].<ref name=\"life_We'r\">{{Cite web| title = We're Gianna Toboni and Isobel Yeung, Correspondents for VICE on HBO, and This Is How We Work| last = Orin | first = Andy| work = Lifehacker| date = | access-date = 7 July 2019| url = https://lifehacker.com/were-gianna-toboni-and-isobel-yeung-correspondents-for-1794935056| quote = Right after I graduated, I moved to China. I wasn\u2019t sure what I wanted to do, except travel and learn a language. I started freelancing for various publications and broadcasters. It felt like Asia was underrepresented in global media coverage, so I was passionate about covering in-depth pieces that brought attention to that part of the world. China is a goldmine for fascinating and complex stories.In 2014, I pitched a piece for Vice News on the Hong Kong protests. We created a 30-minute documentary, allowing us to dig into some of the issues that weren\u2019t being covered in the news headlines.}}</ref> With Vice, she has predominantly been an on-air correspondent and producer for their flagship shows airing on [[HBO]], specializing in long form content and [[interviews]]. She is known for covering stories on [[gender discrimination]] and [[sexual consent]], in the [[United States|US]] and abroad.<ref name=\"marieclaire\">{{cite web|url=https://www.marieclaire.com/culture/news/g4118/the-new-guard-2016/|title=The New Guard: America's 50 Most Influential Women|first1=Lea|last1=Goldman|first2=Rachel|last2=Sklar|website=[[Marie Claire]]|publisher=Marie Claire|date=13 October 2016|access-date=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Yeung went undercover in China to report on the [[Xinjiang re-education camps|mass detention]], family separation and surveillance of the [[Uyghurs]]. She has also reported extensively on the [[Syrian Civil War]]. She has been dating Iranian journalist and filmmaker [[Benjamin Zand]] since 2018.\n\n===Awards and Recognition===\nIn 2019, Isobel Yeung won two [[Emmy Awards]] for her coverage of ''Yemen's Forgotten War''.<ref name=\"viceawards\">{{IMDb title | 6329790 | Vice News Tonight | section= awards }}</ref>  The same year, she was honored with the Marie Colvin Front Page Award for Foreign Correspondence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newswomensclubnewyork.com/fps-index#/2019-front-page-awards|title=2019 Front Page Awards|website=NewswomensClubNewYork.com |publisher=[[Newswomen's Club of New York]]|date=23 October 2019|access-date=14 November 2019}}</ref> In 2017, Yeung won a [[Gracie Award]] for TV National Reporter/Correspondent for her work on ''Afghan Women\u2019s Rights'' for [[Vice (TV series)|Vice on HBO]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://allwomeninmedia.org/gracies/2017-gracie-winners/|title=2017 Gracies Gala Winners|website=All Women in Media|publisher=[[Alliance for Women in Media]]|date=28 March 2017|access-date=14 November 2019}}</ref> She\u2019s previously been featured in the [[Marie Claire]] list of most influential women in the US.<ref name=\"marieclaire\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.hbo.com/vice/cast-and-crew/isobel-yeung Vice News Tonight: Correspondents: Isobel Yeung]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yeung, Isobel}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British journalists]]\n[[Category:British people of Chinese descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Documentary correspondent}}\n{{Peacock|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Isobel Yeung\n| image         = Nic Dawes - Isobel Yeung - Beverly Chase - HBO Vice.jpg\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1986|11|02}} \n| birth_place   = [[Salisbury, United Kingdom]]\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Nottingham]]\n| nationality   = [[British people|British]] \n| occupation    = [[Journalist]] \n| years_active  = \n}}\n'''Isobel Yeung''' is a long-form [[documentary]] [[correspondent]]. She has covered a variety of global stories, including [[war|conflict]], [[terrorism]], [[gender]], [[mental health]], and [[Xinjiang re-education camps|mass detention]]. Her work has earned her two [[Emmy Awards]] and a [[Gracie Award]].\n\n==Biography==\nHer mother is English and father is from [[Hong Kong]].<ref name=\"thew_VICE\">{{Cite web| title = VICE's Isobel Yeung is Breaking The Dress Code| author = | work = The Window| date = | access-date = 7 July 2019| url = https://thewindow.barneys.com/isobel-yeung-breaking-the-dress-code/| quote = Originally from the U.K., Yeung has always had a global perspective, due in part to the fact that her father immigrated to England from Hong Kong in search of a better life}}</ref><ref name=\"poyn_Vice\">{{Cite web| title = Vice goes inside Syria to show what media censorship really looks like - Poynter| author = | work = Poynter| date = 2017-02-23| access-date = 7 July 2019| url = https://www.poynter.org/reporting-editing/2017/vice-goes-inside-syria-to-show-what-media-censorship-really-looks-like/\n| quote = The effort by Yeung \u2014 the child of an English mother and Hong Kong Chinese dad}}</ref> She grew up in [[Salisbury]].\n\nYeung moved to [[China]] after graduating in 2009 from the [[University of Nottingham]].  She freelanced for a number of print publications. Yeung was hired by [[Vice News]] in 2014 and relocated to [[New York City]].<ref name=\"life_We'r\">{{Cite web| title = We're Gianna Toboni and Isobel Yeung, Correspondents for VICE on HBO, and This Is How We Work| last = Orin | first = Andy| work = Lifehacker| date = | access-date = 7 July 2019| url = https://lifehacker.com/were-gianna-toboni-and-isobel-yeung-correspondents-for-1794935056| quote = Right after I graduated, I moved to China. I wasn\u2019t sure what I wanted to do, except travel and learn a language. I started freelancing for various publications and broadcasters. It felt like Asia was underrepresented in global media coverage, so I was passionate about covering in-depth pieces that brought attention to that part of the world. China is a goldmine for fascinating and complex stories.In 2014, I pitched a piece for Vice News on the Hong Kong protests. We created a 30-minute documentary, allowing us to dig into some of the issues that weren\u2019t being covered in the news headlines.}}</ref> With Vice, she has predominantly been an on-air correspondent and producer for their flagship shows airing on [[HBO]], specializing in long form content and [[interviews]]. She is known for covering stories on [[gender discrimination]] and [[sexual consent]], in the [[United States|US]] and abroad.<ref name=\"marieclaire\">{{cite web|url=https://www.marieclaire.com/culture/news/g4118/the-new-guard-2016/|title=The New Guard: America's 50 Most Influential Women|first1=Lea|last1=Goldman|first2=Rachel|last2=Sklar|website=[[Marie Claire]]|publisher=Marie Claire|date=13 October 2016|access-date=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Yeung went undercover in China to report on the [[Xinjiang re-education camps|mass detention]], family separation and surveillance of the [[Uyghurs]]. She has also reported extensively on the [[Syrian Civil War]]. She has been dating Iranian journalist and filmmaker [[Benjamin Zand]] since 2018.\n\n===Awards and Recognition===\nIn 2019, Isobel Yeung won two [[Emmy Awards]] for her coverage of ''Yemen's Forgotten War''.<ref name=\"viceawards\">{{IMDb title | 6329790 | Vice News Tonight | section= awards }}</ref>  The same year, she was honored with the Marie Colvin Front Page Award for Foreign Correspondence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newswomensclubnewyork.com/fps-index#/2019-front-page-awards|title=2019 Front Page Awards|website=NewswomensClubNewYork.com |publisher=[[Newswomen's Club of New York]]|date=23 October 2019|access-date=14 November 2019}}</ref> In 2017, Yeung won a [[Gracie Award]] for TV National Reporter/Correspondent for her work on ''Afghan Women\u2019s Rights'' for [[Vice (TV series)|Vice on HBO]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://allwomeninmedia.org/gracies/2017-gracie-winners/|title=2017 Gracies Gala Winners|website=All Women in Media|publisher=[[Alliance for Women in Media]]|date=28 March 2017|access-date=14 November 2019}}</ref> She\u2019s previously been featured in the [[Marie Claire]] list of most influential women in the US.<ref name=\"marieclaire\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.hbo.com/vice/cast-and-crew/isobel-yeung Vice News Tonight: Correspondents: Isobel Yeung]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yeung, Isobel}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British journalists]]\n[[Category:British people of Chinese descent]]\n", "name_user": "Eisfbnore", "label": "safe", "comment": "WP:EGG", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isobel_Yeung"}
